Google Maps does not have a direct "time travel" endpoint. However, Google Maps does provide features that allow users to view historical imagery through its web interface, particularly in Google Earth and Google Maps when looking at certain locations with satellite imagery available from different times.

If you're interested in accessing Google Maps APIs programmatically, you typically use endpoints for services like Places API, Maps JavaScript API, Directions API, etc. But there isn't a direct API endpoint for accessing historical imagery programmatically.

That said, you can accomplish "time travel" in a conceptual way by integrating the imagery if you have access to Google Earth Engine or any other historical dataset and visualizing them on a map.

Here's a basic example of how to use the Google Maps JavaScript API to display a map. You would need to overlay historical data manually since there is no direct support for timeline or historical imagery via the JavaScript API:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Simple Google Maps Example</title>
    <style>
        /* Set the size of the map */
        #map {
            height: 100%;
        }
        html, body {
            height: 100%;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
        }
    </style>
    <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY"></script>
    <script>
        function initMap() {
            // Create the map centered at a specific location
            var location = { lat: 37.7749, lng: -122.4194 }; // San Francisco
            var map = new google.maps.Map(document.getElementById('map'), {
                zoom: 10,
                center: location
            });

            // You can add markers or other overlays here for historical data
            var marker = new google.maps.Marker({
                position: location,
                map: map,
                title: 'Marker for historical data'
            });

